Rating: 4
Incredibly good, when made with good quality ingredients. I can imagine it would be pretty dull with anaemic supermarket value chicken and canned low-sodium broth. I make this recipe roughly every fortnight during the cold months, and have found a routine that makes it MUCH easier. Firstly, use a large, free-range, corn-fed chicken to make a roast or pot-roast chicken for dinner. Enjoy immensely. When it's cooled, pick the carcass clean, putting any meat aside for the pot pie and dumping all the bones, skin, plate scrapings and leftover gravy into a slow cooker. Throw in the usual stock veggies and seasonings. Fill to the top with water and cook on low all night AND the following day. The next afternoon, about two hours before you want to eat your pot pie, strain stock into a saucepan and chop the vegetables while the it comes to a boil, and then chop up the chicken meat, leek and onions while the vegetables cook. Proceed with the recipe as directed. I find that it takes me about 30 minutes of actual work to make this - 25 minutes to slice, dice and make the filling, and another 5 minutes after it has all rested to roll out the pasty. I use an all-butter, ready-made shortcrust block from the freezer, and just sprinkle the herbs on top as I roll it out. I've made this about a dozen times now, and my personal taste is to use about half the quantity of chicken called for and double the vegetables. I also like to use celery, peas, sweet potato, butternut squash, jerusalem artichokes, chestnut mushrooms, whatever needs to be used from the CSA, and I like to dice things a little smaller (about 1/3 of a an inch cubes). We usually have enough stock to make risotto the next night and then we have pot pie leftovers the night after that. So one really good quality chicken does four meals, and you have the satisfaction of knowing that you haven't wasted a single morsel of food.

