Rating: 4
I have tried many versions of chicken potpie and the basics here work well. The thing with a potpie is that you have a basic way to prepare, and you can add variations with ingredients and steps. Cooked ingredients Sauce to bind it all together Crust, or puff pastry on the side Normally I avoid frozen foods, but you can use here frozen pearl onions and peas. I prefer fresh carrots and greens. A pre cooked rotisserie chicken that you shred the meat from (eliminating skin and bones) works fine and saves a step in cooking the chicken yourself. The thing with doing your own chicken breast is that you can cube the white meat for an attractive presentation. As far a vegetables, I do like to add sautéed sliced mushrooms, frozen peas (simply thawed by draining with water) and fresh carrots, steamed or boiled. You can use the wilted turnip greens, or Swiss chard or spinach. You can add the turnips or use precooked cubed potatoes You can add cooked cubed ham. You can add parboiled pearl onions. Frozen is easy, as you do not have to deal with the skins. For the sauce, which binds it all together, I like this version in this recipe. I prefer to chop rather than slice the leeks. Thyme works very well, and I like a very tiny bit of cayenne to the sauce. You do not have to do a crust: I like the frozen puff pastry shells, baked separately ahead of time and sliced in half. The bottom with some of the filling on the plate and then the cap jauntily placed on top each serving. A sprig of fresh time is like the feather in the cap.

